PAAG
PA POLO ARE CAN AIRWAYS SYSTEM
FRANSPACIFIE DIVISION, TREASURE ISTAND, SAN FRANCISCO, CALIFORNIA
February 19, 1945
OFFICE OF THE
DIVISION MANAGER
PERSONAL
Mr. and Mrs. H. M. Bixby
2 Normandy Road
Bronxville, New York
Dear Mr. and Mrs. Bixby:
As contemplated when I telegraphed you Saturday (Feb-
ruary 17), Catherine arrived in Vallejo that morning,
completed
her
"reporting-in"
procedure,
then came down to Hillsborough
that evening•
Damaris, Mother and I-and, of course, Gretchen
and Alice--are hopeful that Catherine will want to
stay with us
until she leaves.
She is a very
comfortable house
guest and
has already made deep inroads into the affections of Mother and
the children.
Gretchen is distressed, however,
that Catherine,
at her
advanced age, is not long since married and settled darn;
at least she deplored that fact in conversation with Catherine
at dimer Saturday evening•
To the extent Damaris's gas holds out, she plans
to
show Catherine some of the local sights of interest.
When I
get back from Seattle, we will
organize a Chinese chow party
for Catherine
and a few other young folks, at our favorite
restaurant in Chinatown.
I am letting Captain Ingalls and
Bill Mullahey know
Catherine is here, and will notify
them when she leaves.
the meantime
I will try, as far as
In
it is consistent
with Bix's
position in the Company, to prevail upon Naval
Air Priorities
to send Catherine out by Clipper•
On the basis of Jean Kingman's
experience, I am not very optimistic, however.
Sincerely,
L. C. Reynolds
